<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-436-024  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 436 024.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computing Canada  June 22 1989 v15 n13 p30(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Start with automated job scheduling; making the right choice inscheduling and workload management tools.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Rogers, Tina.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The automation of data processing departments should begin withautomated job scheduling and workload management.andP;  The advantagesof automating other data processing functions are eitherdiminished or negated if a scheduling system is not implementedbeforehand.andP;  All job schedulers perform time-driven job submissionand control job dependencies, but there are important differencesbetween basic job schedulers and full-blown workload managementsystems.andP;  Whether or not an organization will be able to automateoperations five years down the road depends on its choice ofsystems.andP;  Users should consider the following guidelines beforepurchasing a workload management system: its functionality, itsability to issue operator commands automatically, its ease of use,and its flexibility.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     AutomationData ProcessingJob SchedulingGuidelinesMIS.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>